/* Main computational kernel. The whole function will be timed,
   including the call and return. */
void kernel_durbin(int n,
                   std::vector<double>& r,
                   std::vector<double>& y)
{
    // Work in the raw backing pointers for maximal performance.
    double* const rptr = r.data();
    double* const yptr = y.data();

    // Temporary buffer allocated once to avoid reallocations inside the loop.
    std::vector<double> z_vec(n, 0.0);
    double* const zptr = z_vec.data();

    // First element of y is always set to –r[0].
    yptr[0] = -rptr[0];

    // β and α are scalar values that will be updated in each iteration.
    double beta  = 1.0;
    double alpha = -rptr[0];

    for (int k = 1; k < n; ++k) {
        // β = (1 – α²)β
        beta = (1.0 - alpha * alpha) * beta;

        // Compute the cross‑correlation sum = Σ r[k‑i‑1] * y[i]
        double sum = 0.0;
        // Manual loop fusion avoids repeated index calculations.
        const int kminus = k - 1;
        for (int i = 0; i < k; ++i)
            sum += rptr[kminus - i] * yptr[i];

        // α = –(r[k] + sum)/β
        alpha = -(rptr[k] + sum) / beta;

        // Update the partial solution in z (uses the symmetry
        // property of the recurrence).
        for (int i = 0; i < k; ++i)
            zptr[i] = yptr[i] + alpha * yptr[k - i - 1];

        // Copy z back to y
        // The compiler can vectorise this copy; we use memcpy for a
        // narrow optimisation in case the vector length is small.
        std::memcpy(yptr, zptr, k * sizeof(double));

        // Set the new value y[k]
        yptr[k] = alpha;
    }
}
```

**Key optimisation points**

1. **Raw pointers** – Operating on raw memory (`double*`) almost eliminates the overhead of `operator[]` bounds checking that the standard library container performs.
2. **Single temporary buffer** – One `z_vec` is allocated outside the main loop; reused each iteration to avoid repeated allocations.
3. **Loop fusion & unrolling** – The inner loops are kept straightforward so the compiler can auto‑vectorise. `memcpy` can help the optimizer replace the element‑wise copy with a specialised block‑copy that may use SIMD instructions.
4. **No OpenMP** – The algorithm is inherently serial due to data dependencies, so threading would provide no benefit.
5. **Compatibility** – The function signature and public behaviour are unchanged; the new implementation is fully deterministic and matches the original exactly.

